Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 05:47:58 No.55625714 Report
Quoted By: >>55625835
>>55625446
>>55625448
That level adjustment helped a lot in boosting the contrast and helping push your piece out of midtones samey-ness.

Some things to possibly consider: avoid thinking that anything in shadow is automatically any form of grey, or that color is an inherent quality of any object. Try experimenting with different cool desaturated colors instead. Think blues, purples, etc. You can also use oranges and reds if you want to give the whole image a warmer feel. Same logic goes for highlights. The more contrast between cool and warm you have in your image, the more dynamic it will feel.

Best way to learn color is to just throw it on the canvas and see what happens. Saturate the shit out of it. Try to balance it out. Learning color relationships through color theory certainly helps, but just trying new things by throwing it on the canvas may surprise you.

Best of luck, I certainly enjoy seeing your work.

Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 06:14:26 No.55626050 Report
Quoted By: >>55626268 >>55631325
>>55625835
White fur doesn't actually have to be "white". White as a color reflects different qualities of light far stronger than other colors, so you can use that to your advantage and 'trick' people into thinking something is white without actually using the color.

As an example: If you were to shine an orange light at a white wall, the wall would appear orange, despite it actually being white. It would be different than shining an orange light at a blue wall, which would instead result in the blue becoming more desaturated, but the wall wouldn't actually appear to turn 'orange'.

This probably makes it more confusing, but maybe you can catch my drift.

Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 06:24:28 No.55626198 Report
Quoted By: >>55626594
>>55626093
>there was the tub color reflecting
Is that the strange gray on the tub you're talking about?

The color of the tub would be darkened by bnnuy sadohw, not grayed. Since white fur is the color of ambient light, any light going from bnnuy to tub to camera would be the same "white" as the ambient light that makes the tub that color so it'd just be less bright. It's when you have something like a red object next to a white object that the white object picks up a bit of red from the light that becomes red-biased by the object before being reflected neutrally by the white object.

Remember that all objects with color are subtractive. Coloring is indicative of what colors weren't absorbed (subtracted).

Shadows do tend to have a bit of a blue cast in art, but that's because cool colors recede so you can get a bit more depth without adding black and killing brightness, and it contrasts with the warm colors that are more common in non-synthetic objects, making them stand out even better.

Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 07:45:14 No.55627131 Report
Quoted By: >>55627527
>>55626773
>low occupancy
Kek or concern?

Ahem.

Sounds like you need to do some actual art drills.

Get your ass to Hobby Lobby or Michaels and buy some canvas panels and super cheap acrylics.
• Zinc/mixing white, not Titanium.
• Ivory/bone black, not Mars.
• Ultramarine or Phthalo blue.
• A medium or light yellow, PY3 or 74 or whatever.
• A quincridone magenta on the red side, PR122 or PV19 probably.
• Yellow ochre or raw sienna for an earthtone.
• Phthalo green blue shade.

Mix, match, make messes. Try to get the most picture you can out of the fewest colors. Use the green with your red specifically to mix a gray, it'll take practice to learn the proportion but once you hit it it's nice for graying without sucking too much life out of the color. For greens in the image don't use the tube green, mix into them.

Do studies, git gud.

You can probably buy a kit with approximately these colors but they'll probably give you titanium white (makes your tints chalky because it's too opaque) and mars black (because it's cheap, and it's way too strong to use to darken without murdering every color it touches).

Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 08:21:32 No.55627527 Report

>>55627131
You can also forgo the black entirely and instead mix your complementary colors straight out of the tube. It'll take a little more practice to get the ratios right, but I find the results to be far more interesting shades than simply adding black, although black will preserve the original hue better.

Also, if anon wants to practice color mixing exercises, I find oils to be far more forgiving than acrylics (albeit a little more expensive and trickier to use due to the extra supplies like mineral oil and paint thinner). Oils dry far slower allowing you to constantly reuse the same palette and experiment with creating different tints, tones, and shades.
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Sat 08 Apr 2023 08:43:27 No.55627717 Report
Quoted By:
>>55627527
I mentioned both black and the red+green complementary mix specifically so Anon can experience and learn the difference, and has a way to darken without having to fiddle with red+green if he's having trouble getting the ratio right.

I didn't mention oil because with acrylic, he can set a panel aside, and make new messes on it the next day. Lots of painting, lots of experimenting, low supply costs, easy to clean. The only problem is you need to kinda work fast since it'll dry on your brush but that's suitable for practicing at the pace of digital art. Oil will have him buying a lot of support and accessory chemicals. Also, reusing the same palette would impede the point of the practice of mixing on the fly and experimenting with color.

And if physical art becomes a hobby, he can add oils. Oil goes fine over acrylic so the experience is useful for laying a ground layer without having to worry about learning the different oil content and drying times of the several pigments, etc.
